From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: panic with full CPU dump if migration
 thread stuck > 3s in multi_cpu_stop

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop() when active_load_balance_cpu_stop() triggers a nested
stop_one_cpu_nowait() via:

  finish_task_switch()
    -> run_balance_callbacks()
      -> sched_balance_rq()  OR  balance_push()
        -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()    <-- re-entrancy while already executing
                                        inside stop_two_cpus / multi_cpu_stop

The outer stop_machine cannot release the stopper until it exits.  The
nested stop work cannot be processed until the stopper is free.  The active
CPU is stuck queuing the nested work with IRQs ON, in PREPARE state.
Non-active CPUs spin at position C of the do-while loop (see below).  The
Qualcomm msm_watchdog fires a bark ~10-11 s later; by then crash context
(call stacks, stopper state, task list) is partially lost.

"No of cores hotplugged: 0" confirms the load-balancer nested stop variant,
NOT the hotplug variant.

This patch detects the deadlock after 3 seconds, emits a full per-CPU
diagnostic dump, and calls panic() -- capturing a clean ramdump well before
the Qualcomm watchdog fires.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu
==========================================================================
smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'.  The original 'int cpu' is a
pre-existing type mismatch against cpumask_test_cpu(unsigned int, ...) and
per_cpu_ptr(..., unsigned int).  Clang 19 warns on every call site via
-Wsigned-unsigned-enum-conversion.  'err' retains int because msdata->fn()
can return negative error codes.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Unconditional jiffies-based deadlock detection at position C
==========================================================================
The multi_cpu_stop() spin loop has three positions:

  do {
      if (curstate < msdata->state) { curstate = ...; switch ... }

      if (is_active)
          ack_state(msdata);                /* A: active CPU only */
      else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
          touch_nmi_watchdog();
          rcu_momentary_eqs();              /* B: non-active, past PREPARE */
      }
      /* C: ALL CPUs every iteration -- not reached from B in PREPARE */

  } while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);

In the PREPARE-state deadlock (IRQs ON on all CPUs):
  - Active CPU:      stuck queuing nested stop -> never acks -> stays at A
  - Non-active CPUs: curstate == PREPARE so "curstate > PREPARE" is FALSE
                     -> position B NOT entered -> they spin at position C

Placing the timeout check inside position B (else-if) is WRONG:
  1. Unreachable when curstate == PREPARE (the actual deadlock state)
  2. Even when reached (DISABLE_IRQ/RUN): local_irq_disable() +
     hard_irq_disable() called -> jiffies frozen -> time_after() always
     false -> detection never fires

The CORRECT placement is position C -- unconditional, after both branches.
jiffies naturally freeze in IRQ-off states, suppressing false positives:

  PREPARE (IRQs ON -- deadlock state):
    HZ=250 (from /proc/config.gz): tick every 4ms -> jiffies++ ->
    after 3*250=750 jiffies (3000ms) -> time_after() true -> panic()

  DISABLE_IRQ / RUN (IRQs OFF):
    local_irq_disable() + hard_irq_disable() -> timer IRQ blocked ->
    jiffies frozen -> time_after() always false -> NO panic (correct!)

CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y (from /proc/config.gz on target):
  tick_nohz_idle_enter() is called ONLY from cpu_idle_loop().
  migration/N threads are SCHED_FIFO RT and never call cpu_idle_loop().
  -> Ticks fire at full HZ=250 during the PREPARE deadlock.

CONFIG_NO_HZ_FULL=n -- not set. No concern.

CONFIG_HZ=250 (from /proc/config.gz):
  STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES = 3 * 250 = 750 jiffies = 3000 ms
  Qualcomm bark_time              = ~9000-11000 ms
  Safety margin before bark       = ~6000 ms -- panic always wins ramdump

==========================================================================
Diagnostics emitted before panic()
==========================================================================
  Sec 1: outer stopper fn + caller on detecting CPU (root cause -- the
         cpu_stop_work that called stop_two_cpus() causing re-entrancy)
  Sec 2: multi_stop_data: state name, num_threads, thread_ack, inner fn
  Sec 3: cpu_online/active/dying masks
          (cpu_dying_mask==0 confirms load-balancer variant vs hotplug)
  Sec 4: per-CPU stopper state for ALL online CPUs (lockless snapshot)
  Sec 5: dump_stack() for the stuck migration/N thread
  Sec 6: trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() -- IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE to all CPUs
          (same IPI path as Qualcomm msm_watchdog ping_other_cpus)
  Sec 7: show_state() -- SysRq-T equivalent

==========================================================================
Build fixes vs previous revisions
==========================================================================
  [FIX-A] dump helpers placed AFTER struct multi_stop_data.
    Inserting after enum multi_stop_state (line 167) but before
    struct multi_stop_data (~line 180) caused Clang 19 to treat
    'struct multi_stop_data' in function parameters as a new forward
    declaration, triggering [-Werror,-Wvisibility].

  [FIX-C] Deadlock detection at position C (unconditional), not inside
    the else-if block (position B).  The else-if closing brace must be
    a CONTEXT line, not an added line.

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================
  - Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
  - No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
  - Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible
  - trigger_all_cpu_backtrace(): <linux/nmi.h> already in stop_machine.c
  - show_state(): <linux/sched/debug.h> -- always present in GKI
  - jiffies / HZ / time_after(): unconditionally available

Bug: b/XXXXXXXXX
Change-Id: Ixxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
Signed-off-by: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
---
 kernel/stop_machine.c | 257 ++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 249 insertions(+), 8 deletions(-)

diff --git a/kernel/stop_machine.c b/kernel/stop_machine.c
index 5d2d056..prodfix1 100644
--- a/kernel/stop_machine.c
+++ b/kernel/stop_machine.c
@@ -10,9 +10,12 @@
 #include <linux/compiler.h>
 #include <linux/completion.h>
 #include <linux/cpu.h>
+#include <linux/cpumask.h>
+#include <linux/jiffies.h>
 #include <linux/init.h>
 #include <linux/kthread.h>
 #include <linux/export.h>
 #include <linux/percpu.h>
+#include <linux/sched/debug.h>
 #include <linux/sched.h>
 #include <linux/stop_machine.h>
 #include <linux/interrupt.h>
@@ -25,6 +28,26 @@
 #include <linux/nmi.h>
 #include <linux/sched/wake_q.h>
 
+/*
+ * STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES -- jiffies-based panic threshold.
+ *
+ * CONFIG_HZ=250 (confirmed /proc/config.gz on target): 1 jiffy = 4ms.
+ * 3 * 250 = 750 jiffies = 3000ms.  Qualcomm bark_time ~9-11s.
+ * Safety margin ~6000ms -- panic always wins the ramdump capture race.
+ *
+ * jiffies freeze when IRQs are disabled (DISABLE_IRQ/RUN states) so the
+ * timeout auto-suppresses in those states without any explicit state check.
+ *
+ * CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y (target): safe because migration/N threads are
+ * SCHED_FIFO RT and never call cpu_idle_loop() -- ticks fire at full rate.
+ * CONFIG_NO_HZ_FULL=n -- not set on target. No concern.
+ */
+#define STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES		(3 * HZ)
+
+/* Compile-time guard: catches misconfigured HZ before runtime. */
+static_assert(HZ > 0, "HZ must be > 0");
+
 /*
  * Structure to determine completion condition and record errors. May
  * be shared by works on different cpus.
@@ -195,6 +218,184 @@ struct multi_stop_data {
 	atomic_t thread_ack;
 };
 
+/*
+ * stopper_state_names[] -- human-readable names for enum multi_stop_state.
+ *
+ * [FIX-A] Placed here, after BOTH enum multi_stop_state AND
+ * struct multi_stop_data, so that:
+ *   - The designated-initialiser constants [MULTI_STOP_x] are in scope.
+ *   - The dump helpers below can reference 'struct multi_stop_data *' in
+ *     function parameters without triggering Clang 19's [-Wvisibility].
+ */
+static const char * const stopper_state_names[] = {
+	[MULTI_STOP_NONE]        = "NONE",
+	[MULTI_STOP_PREPARE]     = "PREPARE",
+	[MULTI_STOP_DISABLE_IRQ] = "DISABLE_IRQ",
+	[MULTI_STOP_RUN]         = "RUN",
+	[MULTI_STOP_EXIT]        = "EXIT",
+};
+static_assert(ARRAY_SIZE(stopper_state_names) == MULTI_STOP_EXIT + 1,
+	      "stopper_state_names[] out of sync with enum multi_stop_state");
+
+/* -----------------------------------------------------------------------
+ * Stopper deadlock diagnostic helpers.
+ * All noinline -- only called from the panic path.
+ * ----------------------------------------------------------------------- */
+
+/**
+ * stopper_dump_one_cpu() - print per-cpu stopper state to dmesg
+ * @cpu: target CPU (unsigned int -- matches smp_processor_id() return type)
+ *
+ * Lockless read of cpu_stopper -- intentional on the panic path.
+ * Best-effort snapshot preferred over missing the dump entirely.
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_dump_one_cpu(unsigned int cpu)
+{
+	struct cpu_stopper *st = per_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper, cpu);
+	struct cpu_stop_work *w;
+	int n = 0;
+
+	pr_emerg("  [CPU%u stopper] task=%-16s enabled=%d\n",
+		 cpu,
+		 st->thread ? st->thread->comm : "(null)",
+		 st->enabled);
+	pr_emerg("                 fn=%pS  caller=%pS\n",
+		 st->fn, (void *)st->caller);
+
+	/* Walk pending work list -- lockless, best-effort. */
+	list_for_each_entry(w, &st->works, list) {
+		pr_emerg("    pending[%d]: fn=%pS  caller=%pS\n",
+			 n++, w->fn, (void *)w->caller);
+		if (n >= 8) {
+			pr_emerg("    ... (truncated at 8 entries)\n");
+			break;
+		}
+	}
+	if (!n)
+		pr_emerg("    pending works: (none)\n");
+}
+
+/**
+ * stopper_dump_msdata() - print multi_stop_data fields to dmesg
+ * @msdata:    shared state machine data for this stop operation
+ * @stuck_cpu: CPU that detected the timeout
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_dump_msdata(struct multi_stop_data *msdata,
+					 unsigned int stuck_cpu)
+{
+	int state = READ_ONCE(msdata->state);
+	const char *sname;
+
+	sname = ((unsigned int)state < ARRAY_SIZE(stopper_state_names) &&
+		 stopper_state_names[state])
+		? stopper_state_names[state] : "UNKNOWN";
+
+	pr_emerg("=== multi_stop_data (CPU%u) ===\n", stuck_cpu);
+	pr_emerg("  state       : %d (%s)\n", state, sname);
+	pr_emerg("  num_threads : %u\n", msdata->num_threads);
+	pr_emerg("  thread_ack  : %d  <- CPUs NOT yet acked\n",
+		 atomic_read(&msdata->thread_ack));
+	pr_emerg("  inner fn    : %pS\n", msdata->fn);
+	pr_emerg("  active_cpus : %*pbl\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(msdata->active_cpus
+				 ? msdata->active_cpus : cpu_online_mask));
+}
+
+/**
+ * stopper_deadlock_dump() - emit 7-section diagnostic dump before panic()
+ * @cpu:       detecting CPU id (unsigned int)
+ * @msdata:    shared multi_stop_data for this stop operation
+ * @elapsed_j: jiffies elapsed since spin entry (display only)
+ *
+ * noinline so migration/N appears clearly at the top of the call stack.
+ * Returns to caller which must call panic().
+ */
+static noinline void stopper_deadlock_dump(unsigned int cpu,
+					   struct multi_stop_data *msdata,
+					   unsigned long elapsed_j)
+{
+	struct cpu_stopper *st = this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper);
+	unsigned int c;
+
+	pr_emerg("\n");
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+	pr_emerg("STOPPER DEADLOCK: migration/%u stuck in\n"
+		 "multi_cpu_stop for ~%u ms\n"
+		 "Suspected cause: nested cpu_stop_queue_work() re-entrancy\n"
+		 "  e.g. active_load_balance_cpu_stop()\n"
+		 "       -> finish_task_switch() -> run_balance_callbacks()\n"
+		 "       -> sched_balance_rq() -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()\n"
+		 "  while already executing inside stop_two_cpus().\n",
+		 cpu, jiffies_to_msecs(elapsed_j));
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+
+	/*
+	 * Section 1: OUTER stopper -- the cpu_stop_work that called
+	 * stop_two_cpus() and caused the nested re-entrancy deadlock.
+	 */
+	pr_emerg("=== offending CPU%u outer stopper ===\n", cpu);
+	pr_emerg("  outer fn    : %pS\n", st->fn);
+	pr_emerg("  outer caller: %pS\n", (void *)st->caller);
+
+	/* Section 2: state machine position and ack count */
+	stopper_dump_msdata(msdata, cpu);
+
+	/*
+	 * Section 3: CPU masks.
+	 *   cpu_dying_mask == 0 -> load-balancer nested stop (our case)
+	 *   cpu_dying_mask != 0 -> hotplug-triggered variant
+	 */
+	pr_emerg("=== CPU masks ===\n");
+	pr_emerg("  cpu_online_mask : %*pbl\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(cpu_online_mask));
+	pr_emerg("  cpu_active_mask : %*pbl\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(cpu_active_mask));
+	pr_emerg("  cpu_dying_mask  : %*pbl  (non-zero = hotplug variant)\n",
+		 cpumask_pr_args(cpu_dying_mask));
+
+	/* Section 4: per-CPU stopper state for every online CPU */
+	pr_emerg("=== per-CPU stopper state (all online CPUs) ===\n");
+	for_each_online_cpu(c)
+		stopper_dump_one_cpu(c);
+
+	/* Section 5: call stack of the stuck migration/N thread */
+	pr_emerg("=== migration/%u call stack ===\n", cpu);
+	dump_stack();
+
+	/* Section 6: IPI backtrace -- same mechanism as Qualcomm watchdog
+	 * ping_other_cpus().  trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() uses
+	 * IPI_CPU_BACKTRACE; declared in <linux/nmi.h> (already included).
+	 */
+	pr_emerg("=== IPI backtrace for ALL CPUs ===\n");
+	trigger_all_cpu_backtrace();
+
+	/* Section 7: all task states -- SysRq-T equivalent. */
+	pr_emerg("=== all task states (SysRq-T equivalent) ===\n");
+	show_state();
+
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+	pr_emerg("Calling panic() to trigger ramdump/minidump.\n"
+		 "bark_time (~9-11s) > 3s threshold => ramdump wins.\n");
+	pr_emerg("=====================================================\n");
+}
+
+/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------- */
+
 static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 {
 	struct multi_stop_data *msdata = data;
@@ -209,8 +410,12 @@ static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 	struct multi_stop_data *msdata = data;
 	enum multi_stop_state newstate, curstate = MULTI_STOP_NONE;
-	int cpu = smp_processor_id(), err = 0;
+	/*
+	 * FIX: smp_processor_id() returns unsigned int.  'int cpu' is a
+	 * pre-existing mismatch vs cpumask_test_cpu(unsigned int, ...) and
+	 * per_cpu_ptr(..., unsigned int).  Clang 19 warns at every call site.
+	 * 'err' stays int: msdata->fn() can return negative error codes.
+	 */
+	unsigned int cpu = smp_processor_id();
+	int err = 0, timed_out = 0;
 	const struct cpumask *cpumask;
 	unsigned long flags;
+	unsigned long start_jiffies;
 	bool is_active;
 
@@ -232,6 +437,12 @@ static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 		is_active = cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, cpumask);
 	}
 
+	/*
+	 * Snapshot jiffies before entering the spin loop.
+	 * jiffies advances via the timer tick interrupt -- the same subsystem
+	 * as the Qualcomm msm_watchdog pet_timer kthread.
+	 * See STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES comment above for full rationale.
+	 */
+	start_jiffies = jiffies;
+
 	/* Simple state machine */
 	do {
 		/* Chill out and ensure we re-read multi_stop_state. */
@@ -250,9 +461,47 @@ static int multi_cpu_stop(void *data)
 		} else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
 			/*
 			 * At this stage all other CPUs we depend on must spin
-			 * in the same loop. Any reason for hard-lockup should
-			 * be detected and reported on their side.
+			 * in the same loop.  Touch the NMI watchdog and suppress
+			 * RCU stall warnings while we spin.
 			 */
 			touch_nmi_watchdog();
-			/* Also suppress RCU CPU stall warnings. */
 			rcu_momentary_eqs();
 		}
+
+		/*
+		 * [FIX-C] Deadlock detection -- position C, unconditional.
+		 *
+		 * Placed AFTER the closing '}' of the else-if block so it runs
+		 * for ALL CPUs in ALL states, including PREPARE (deadlock state):
+		 *
+		 *   PREPARE (IRQs ON):
+		 *     Active CPU:     stuck queuing nested stop -> no ack -> A
+		 *     Non-active CPUs: curstate==PREPARE -> B not entered -> C
+		 *     HZ=250: jiffies tick every 4ms -> after
+		 *     3*HZ (3*250=750 = 3000ms) ->
+		 *     time_after() true -> panic()
+		 *
+		 *   DISABLE_IRQ / RUN (IRQs OFF):
+		 *     local_irq_disable() + hard_irq_disable() block timer IRQ
+		 *     -> jiffies freeze -> time_after() always false -> no panic
+		 *
+		 * WRONG placement: inside "else if (curstate > PREPARE)" (B):
+		 *   1. Unreachable when curstate == PREPARE (actual deadlock).
+		 *   2. When reached (DISABLE_IRQ/RUN): IRQs OFF, jiffies frozen
+		 *      -> time_after() never true -> detection never fires.
+		 *
+		 * CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y: safe because migration/N threads are
+		 * SCHED_FIFO RT and never call cpu_idle_loop() -> ticks fire
+		 * at full HZ=250 in PREPARE state.
+		 *
+		 * timed_out prevents re-entering dump/panic before panic() wins.
+		 */
+		if (!timed_out &&
+		    time_after(jiffies,
+			       start_jiffies + STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES)) {
+			unsigned long elapsed_j = jiffies - start_jiffies;
+
+			timed_out = 1;
+			stopper_deadlock_dump(cpu, msdata, elapsed_j);
+			panic("migration/%u: stuck in multi_cpu_stop "
+			      "for ~%u ms | state=%s thread_ack=%d "
+			      "stop_fn=%pS | nested stop_machine "
+			      "deadlock | see ramdump for full trace\n",
+			      cpu,
+			      jiffies_to_msecs(elapsed_j),
+			      stopper_state_names[
+				min_t(unsigned int,
+				      (unsigned int)READ_ONCE(msdata->state),
+				      MULTI_STOP_EXIT)],
+			      atomic_read(&msdata->thread_ack),
+			      this_cpu_ptr(&cpu_stopper)->fn);
+		}
+
 	} while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);
 
-- 
2.43.0
